tional, comparative view of the changing political landscape, examining the degree to which the centre-left project is exhausted and is able to renew its message in a neo-liberal age. Using case studies from the UK, Germany, Spain, France, Australia and New Zealand contributors argue that despite different local and specific contexts, the mainstream centre-left is beset by a range of common challenges. Analysis focuses on institutional and structural factors, the role of key individuals, especially party leaders, and the atrophy of progressive ideas in explaining why the centre-left is currently in retreat. Why the Left Loses is aimed at stimulating wider debate about the fortunes of the centre-left.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aNeoliberalism. 0aRight and left (Political science). 0aSocialism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh1 aBeech, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelfrage, Claes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerman, Sheri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuperus, René, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Francesco-Mayot, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuncan, Grant, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJun, Uwe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKuisma, Mikko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManwaring, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula